Conclusion: We've got 3 dataframes with the info on sessions, orders and marketing expenses for the Yandex.Afisha service from June 2017 till end of May 2018. I will analyze the data in order to draw conclusions on users behaviour coming from different devices and add sources.¶

2. How many sessions are there per day? (One user might have more than one session.)¶

Let's calculate the number of sessions by the users entering the service from desktop and touch devices and plot it on one graph:

We see the peak of users coming from both device types in December 2017. Most probably the reason is New Year and people bying presents for the holiday and new year vacations. There are more users coming from desktop devices than from mobile devices. It would be interesting to see the dynamics in 2019-2020 because people use more and more mobile devices. If desktop is still leading it may mean that the mobile version is less convinient for users.

4. How often do users come back?¶

Let's find out user cohorts lifetime deviding them into weeks and months. We will analyze the data for 2017 and 2018 separatly in order not to overload us with the info.

first_session_date.name = 'first_session_date'
first_session_date

visits_2['cohort_lifetime'] = pd.to_datetime(visits_2['session_week_2']) - visits_2['first_session_week']
visits_2['cohort_lifetime'] = visits_2['cohort_lifetime'] / np.timedelta64(1,'W')
visits_2['cohort_lifetime'] = visits_2['cohort_lifetime'].round().astype(int)

Cohorts by weeks for 2017:

In [25]:
cohorts =visits_2.groupby(['first_session_week','cohort_lifetime']).agg({'uid':'nunique'}).reset_index() 
initial_users_count = cohorts[cohorts['cohort_lifetime'] == 0][['first_session_week','uid']]
initial_users_count = initial_users_count.rename(columns={'uid':'cohort_users'})
cohorts = cohorts.merge(initial_users_count,on='first_session_week')
cohorts['retention'] = cohorts['uid']/cohorts['cohort_users']
cohorts['year'] = cohorts['first_session_week'].dt.year
cohorts_2017 = cohorts.query('year == 2017')
retention_pivot_2017 = cohorts_2017.pivot_table(index='first_session_week',columns='cohort_lifetime',values='retention',aggfunc='sum')

Step 3.¶

Conclusion:¶

We have observed the data on Yandex.Afisha marketing and users behaviour indications for 12 months from June 2017 till end of May 2018. Our goal was to analyze the performance of different add sources over time and formulate the recomendations for the upcoming period.
We have studied 3 dataframes with the info on the visits of the website, orders done during 12 months and marketing info for this given period of time.
First of all, the revenue for the given period of time was lower than the marketing expenses. This may be a sign for concern, but to draw more conclusions, we need to observe the service for the longer period of time to see the dynamics.
It is clear that there much more users coming from the desktop devices - meaning from the stable environment (home or work), than from the mobile devices. As per current time people are used to buy many things on the go, on the way to work, or home. May be the mobile version of the service or its application is less convinient and some efforts should be put in developing it.
In regards of time indicators - the bigest numbers of website visits and orders are observed prior and during the New Year holidays. That effect is probably achieved due to the growth of the purchase tendency - buying presents and tickets for the New Year vacations entertainment or/and succsessful marketing campaigns. More targeting campaigns can be launched prior other holidays and vacations.
In general the ROMI indicators are low for all the add sources - starting from 6.66% for the most costly add source #3, ending with 22.8% from the source #4 that brought the majority of users to the service. In the upcoming period I would recommend to focus on the add source #4 and 5.
As for the retention behaviour - the retention rate drops drasticly on the second month after the service was used for the first time and never reaches the level of the first month, not even close. It can be explained by the fact that people do not buy tickets that often, but may be some efforts can be put in the retention of the clients (some discounts for the second and further purchase or someting else).
